Key Findings

This section summarizes everything discovered during EDA.

1. Income Distribution
Most customers belong to the low and middle-income groups.
Only a small number of customers have very high incomes.

Business Finding:

The company should maintain affordable product offerings while also creating premium campaigns for high-income customers.

2. Age Distribution
Most customers are between 45 and 60 years old.
Very few customers belong to the younger or very old age groups.

Business Finding:

Middle-aged customers represent the largest customer segment and should remain the primary target audience.

3. Spending Behavior
Most customers have relatively low total spending.
A small group of customers contributes significantly higher spending.

Business Finding:

High-spending customers are valuable and should receive personalized offers and loyalty rewards.

4. Campaign Response
Customers with higher income are more likely to respond.
Customers with higher total spending are also more likely to respond.
Age shows only a weak influence on campaign response.

Business Finding:

Income and spending behavior are stronger predictors of campaign success than age.

5. Customer Purchasing Behavior
Customers who make more purchases generally spend more.
Purchase frequency positively influences total revenue.

Business Finding:

Encouraging repeat purchases can significantly increase overall sales.

